[5] FAO update
Date: Fri, 3 Feb 2006
From: Akiko Kamata <Akiko.Kamata@fao.org>
Source: FAO AIDE News, Issue No 38, 31 Jan 2006 [edited]

Update on the Avian Influenza situation: Country situation
----------------------------------------------------------
Turkey:
On 27 Dec 2005, a new outbreak was reported in poultry in eastern
Igdir Province. Since then, HPAI infection has been confirmed in
backyard poultry in 57 places [situated within] 27 provinces [see the
map in commentary to item 4 above]. Protection and surveillance zones
have been declared and susceptible animals in the protection zones
have been culled with compensation given. In Turkey, 98 percent of
the poultry is chicken. Of its approximately 300 million poultry, 10
million are raised in backyards. The national AI control policy is
stamping out on confirmed infected holdings and culling in backyard
systems within a 3-km radius. Province-wide culling has been
implemented in 3 provinces.
Culling on suspicion has been practised since a change in legislation
in late 2005. As of 30 Jan 2006, 1 596 000 poultry have been culled.
Laboratory tests conducted at Turkey's National Influenza Centre in
Ankara have confirmed 21 cases of human infection in Agri, Ankara,
Corum, Kastamonu, Samsun, Sanliurfa, Siirt, Sivas and Van Provinces.
Of these cases, 4 from Dogubayazit, Van Province have been fatal. An
international team of health professionals (FAO, OIE, WHO, EC/ECDC)
has assessed the country situation, epidemiological facts (human and
animal), and country needs.
Cyprus:
Preliminary test results of dead birds in Indzhirli Village in the
north part of Cyprus are being investigated for H5.
Romania:
Since October [2005], Romania has detected HPAI H5N1 in 25 places in
its southern and southeastern counties of Tulcea, Braila, Buzau,
Ialomita and Calarasi. On 10 Jan 2006, deaths of poultry were
reported in Ciresu and Dudesti, Braila Department and H5N1 infection
was confirmed. There are 7 active outbreaks: 3 villages in the
Braila, 3 in Ialomita and one in Calarasi. Since the beginning of
outbreaks, more than 53 000 birds have died or been culled.
Romania has adopted a zoning strategy based on risk levels to stop
further spread of disease: zone 0 (Infected Districts) with livestock
movement ban, disinfection, surveillance, confinement of poultry,
restriction of traffic, hunting and fishing ban; and zone 1 (all
districts bordering zone 0) with movement and trade ban of poultry
and pigs, disinfection, surveillance, confinement of poultry have
been established. The latest cases [were recorded] on 10 Jan 2006 in
Ciresu and Dudesti Villages in Braila Country.
Russia:
No new outbreaks have been reported in poultry since late December
2005. Dead pigeons were found in Leninsk District, Murmansk Oblast.
Samples from all poultry farms in the area were sent to the
laboratory in St. Petersburg, with negative results. Antibodies
against AI have been detected in 2 workers out of 450 that have been
sampled in 15 poultry-farming facilities in the Rostov Oblast.
Ukraine:
Since the last AIDEnews, outbreaks have been suspected / confirmed in
Beregove, Predmostnoye, Prymorske, Solar, Soniatchne and Zolotoie
Pole Villages in the Crimean Peninsula. H5N1 infection was also
detected in synanthropic [peridomestic] birds in the City of
Sevastopol. The government veterinary services imposed a standstill
order on all local poultry movements and instituted quarantine
perimeters 3 km around infected villages with an additional 10-km
buffer zone. AI outbreaks were reported in turkeys in Tsvitochne
village, Bilohirsk District, and in Flower Village, Belogorsky,
Crimea on 29 Jan 2006. A total of 137 wild birds have died in Alushta
on 27 Jan and were confirmed as having AI. Deaths of 217 wild birds
were also reported in Partenit on 29 Jan. As of 19 Jan 2006, more
than 200 000 poultry have died or been culled. Quarantine measures
have been lifted in 16 villages in 6 districts. As of 25 Jan 2006,
the total number of quarantined places is 9 (Feodosiya district (4),
Kirovskiy district (4) and Dzhankoyskiy district (1)).
China:
On 22 Dec 2006, H5N1 cases were found in chickens and ducks in
Liuyan, Da Zhu County, Sichuan Province; 1800 birds died and 12 900
were culled. Another outbreak was reported on 1 Jan 2006 in Wudang
Village in Guizhou province; 16 000 quails died and 42 000 birds were
culled. Since the last AIDEnews, human cases have been confirmed in
Fujan, Guangxi, Jiangxi, Hunan and Sichuan Provinces. Some human
cases were reported from provinces where no case in poultry has been
officially reported.
A 29-year-old woman from Chengdu City, Sichuan Province [who] died on
23 Jan 2006 was infected with H5N1.
Hong Kong SAR:
H5N1 virus was detected in a dead magpie robin found in Tai Po
village in New Territories on 10 Jan 206, and in an oriental magpie
robin found dead on 26 Jan 2006.
Hong Kong has collected 9000 samples from dead birds in 2005. All 8
chicken farms near [the site] where the [infected] bird was found
have been inspected and no sign of AI was found.
Indonesia:
More than 21 000 chickens have died in Indramayu, Sukabumi, Subang,
Cirebon regencies and Ciberon municipality, West Java over the last 2
months. At least 6 human cases have been suspected within 10 days in
a village in Indramayu, West Java, another 2 cases in East Jakarta
and one in south Jakarta. According to WHO, 3 cases were confirmed
[so far in] 2006, of which all 3 were fatal. The country's
presentation related to the AI situation and control is posted at:
<http://www.who.int/entity/mediacentre/events/2005/04_Indonesia_Sri_mulhani.pdf>.
Viet Nam:Viet Nam completed its first round [of] nationwide
vaccination in early Jan 2006, and currently post-vaccination
surveillance [is being] conducted. As of 22 Jan 2006, 7600 serum
samples have been tested with protective rates reaching 86.3 percent
for duck and 82.6 percent for chicken. Swab samples were also taken
for analyses, and the results of the 627 swab samples were negative
for H5 strain.
Joseph Domenech
Chief, Animal Health Service
Animal Production & Health Division
Food and Agriculture Organisation of the United Nations
--
Akiko Kamata
<Akiko.Kamata@fao.org>
[The report includes maps; it is soon expected to become available at
<http://www.fao.org/ag/againfo/subjects/en/health/diseases-cards/avian_update.html>.
- Mod.AS]
